{{other uses|As the Crow Flies (disambiguation)}}
{{italic title}}
'''''As the crow flies''''', similar to ''in a [[wikt:beeline|beeline]]'', is an [[idiom]] for the most direct path between two points. This meaning is attested from the early 19th century,<ref name="Allen"/><ref name="Knowles"/> and appeared in [[Charles Dickens]]'s novel ''[[Oliver Twist]]'':

{{quote|We cut over the fields at the back with him between us – straight as the crow flies – through hedge and ditch.<ref name="Allen"/>}}

According to [[BBC Focus]], "'As the crow flies' is a pretty common saying but it isn't particularly accurate".<ref name=BBC>Villazon, Luis.  [http://www.sciencefocus.com/article/do-crows-actually-fly-straight-line “Do crows actually fly in a straight line?”], [[BBC Focus]] (August 30, 2017).</ref>  Crows do not swoop in the air like [[swallow]]s or [[starling]]s, but they often circle above their nests.<ref name=BBC />  Crows do conspicuously fly alone across open country, but neither crows nor bees (as in “beeline”) fly in particularly straight lines.<ref name=BBC /> Before modern navigational methods were introduced, Crows were kept upon ships and released when land was sought. Crows instinctively fly towards land.<ref>http://see-the-sea.org/nautical/naut-body.htm</ref>

