{{short description|Ancient microcontinent, containing central Chile and western Argentina}}
{{Geology of the Andes}}
'''Chilenia''' was an ancient [[microcontinent]] or [[terrane]] whose history affected many of the older rocks of central [[Chile]] and western [[Argentina]]. It was once separated by [[oceanic crust]] from the [[Cuyania]] terrane to which it accreted at ~420-390 Ma when Cuyania was already amalgamated with [[Gondwana]].<ref>[http://sp.lyellcollection.org/cgi/content/abstract/246/1/305] Rapalini, A.E. 2005. The accretionary history of southern South America from the latest Proterozoic to the Late Palaeozoic: some palaeomagnetic constraints. From: Vaughan, A. R M., Leat, P. T. & [[Robert John Pankhurst|Pankhurst, R. J,]] (eds). Terrane Processes at the Margins of Gondwana. Geological Society, London, Special Publications, 246, 305-328.</ref>

